7.1.9 - M365SR09: Data Sovereignty and Foreign Access Risks
ISM controls:
•	Control: 0874; Revision: 4; Updated: Jun-21; Applicability: All; OS: All (Data residency for cloud services)
•	Control: 1510; Revision: 2; Updated: Dec-22; Applicability: All; OS: All (Evaluating legal and privacy risks associated with cloud service providers)
•	Control: 0071; Revision: 7; Updated: Sep-23; Applicability: All; OS: All (Protection of data at rest within cloud environments)
________________________________________
Current Risk
Information repositories for M365 reside in regions both inside and outside of Australia which may present data sovereignty or ownership issues, establishing concern over the capability for foreign powers to leverage their authority to intercept or otherwise access agency data.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MAJOR	=	HIGH
________________________________________
Recommendations:
1.	Enforce Australian Data Residency: Configure M365 Multi-Geo Capabilities or Tenant Settings to ensure all primary data at rest (Exchange Online, SharePoint, and OneDrive) is strictly pinned to the Australian geo-locations.
2.	Deploy Customer Key with Availability Key: Implement Microsoft Purview Customer Key to provide the agency with an additional layer of control over encryption keys, ensuring data remains unreadable even if foreign legal processes grant access to physical storage.
3.	Formalise Data Sovereignty Agreements: Review and update cloud service agreements to ensure they align with the Protective Security Policy Framework (PSPF) and the Digital Transformation Agency (DTA) hosting strategy.
- Treatment #1
•	Data Location Audit: Utilise the Microsoft 365 Admin Centre to verify the current "Data Location" for all core services and initiate a data migration for any services residing outside of Australia.
•	Encryption Management: Deploy Azure Key Vault to manage agency-controlled encryption keys, ensuring that the agency maintains the ability to revoke access to encrypted content.
•	Supply Chain Risk Assessment: Conduct a comprehensive security assessment of the cloud service provider’s legal jurisdiction and compliance with Australian privacy principles.
________________________________________
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
By pinning data at rest to Australian shores and maintaining control over encryption keys, the agency significantly mitigates the risk of foreign jurisdictional interference. While the provider's global operations still present a residual "Major" consequence in a worst-case scenario, the likelihood of unauthorised foreign access to readable agency data is reduced to "Unlikely."
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
UNLIKELY	x	MAJOR	=	HIGH

